window.DOCS_INDEX = [{"kind":"chapter","href":"index.html","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","text":" The chapters are ordered, but modular. Open the sidebar on the left to jump around, or use the Next button at the bottom of every page for a linear path. Tap ⌘K (or / ) any time to search across every chapter and section.","snippet":"The chapters are ordered, but modular. Open the sidebar on the left to jump around, or use the Next button at the bottom of every page for a linear path. Tap ⌘K (or / ) any time to search across every chapter and section."},{"kind":"section","href":"index.html#foundations-chapters-01-04","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","heading":"Foundations · Chapters 01–04","text":"Foundations · Chapters 01–04 What emdash is, why it exists, and the platforms it rides on. Chapter 01 Concept What is emdash? The pitch, the license, and the four WordPress problems it targets. Chapter 02 Concept How emdash works The mental model — an Astro integration with D1 / R2 / KV bindings and a plugin sandbox. Chapter 03 Concept Cloudflare primer Workers, Wrangler, D1, R2, KV, and the bindings concept — all in ten minutes. Chapter 04 Concept Astro primer Islands, content collections, the Cloudflare adapter, and emdash's two hook files.","snippet":"What emdash is, why it exists, and the platforms it rides on. Chapter 01 Concept What is emdash? The pitch, the license, and the four WordPress problems it targets. Chapter 02 Concept How emdash works The mental model — an Astro integration with D1 / R2 / KV bindings and a plugin sandbox. Chapter 03 Concept Cloudflare primer Workers, Wrangler, D1, R2, KV, and the bindings concept — all in ten minutes. Chapter 04 Concept Astro primer Islands, content collections, the Cloudflare adapter, and emdash's two hook files."},{"kind":"section","href":"index.html#get-started-chapters-05-06","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","heading":"Get started · Chapters 05–06","text":"Get started · Chapters 05–06 From scaffold to a running dev server in five minutes. Chapter 05 Guide Getting started Scaffold your first emdash site, bootstrap the DB, and open the admin panel. Chapter 06 Guide Template tour The five starter templates, their structure, and the Node vs Cloudflare split.","snippet":"From scaffold to a running dev server in five minutes. Chapter 05 Guide Getting started Scaffold your first emdash site, bootstrap the DB, and open the admin panel. Chapter 06 Guide Template tour The five starter templates, their structure, and the Node vs Cloudflare split."},{"kind":"section","href":"index.html#build-chapters-07-10","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","heading":"Build · Chapters 07–10","text":"Build · Chapters 07–10 Hands-on tutorials. You'll come out with a real, typed, extensible site. Chapter 07 Guide Content modeling Define content types in the admin, regenerate types, query them from pages. Chapter 08 Tutorial Adding pages Add static, dynamic, and filtered pages. Plus JSON and RSS endpoints. Chapter 09 Tutorial Customizing templates Change colors, fonts, layouts, components, and seed content. Chapter 10 Tutorial Building for a new content type End-to-end build of a project type: schema, types, list, detail, deploy.","snippet":"Hands-on tutorials. You'll come out with a real, typed, extensible site. Chapter 07 Guide Content modeling Define content types in the admin, regenerate types, query them from pages. Chapter 08 Tutorial Adding pages Add static, dynamic, and filtered pages. Plus JSON and RSS endpoints. Chapter 09 Tutorial Customizing templates Change colors, fonts, layouts, components, and seed content. Chapter 10 Tutorial Building for a new content type End-to-end build of a project type: schema, types, list, detail, deploy."},{"kind":"section","href":"index.html#ship-chapters-11-12","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","heading":"Ship · Chapters 11–12","text":"Ship · Chapters 11–12 Push to Cloudflare, extend with plugins. Chapter 11 Guide Deploying to Cloudflare From wrangler login to a live URL — step by step. Chapter 12 Concept Plugins The V8-sandboxed plugin model, first-party plugins, and the built-in MCP server.","snippet":"Push to Cloudflare, extend with plugins. Chapter 11 Guide Deploying to Cloudflare From wrangler login to a live URL — step by step. Chapter 12 Concept Plugins The V8-sandboxed plugin model, first-party plugins, and the built-in MCP server."},{"kind":"section","href":"index.html#reference-chapters-13-14","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","heading":"Reference · Chapters 13–14","text":"Reference · Chapters 13–14 Come back to these when you're searching for a specific function or fix. Chapter 13 Ref API reference Every public export from emdash and friends — content, taxonomy, settings, SEO, search. Chapter 14 Ref Troubleshooting Common gotchas, further reading, and a 5-day learning path.","snippet":"Come back to these when you're searching for a specific function or fix. Chapter 13 Ref API reference Every public export from emdash and friends — content, taxonomy, settings, SEO, search. Chapter 14 Ref Troubleshooting Common gotchas, further reading, and a 5-day learning path."},{"kind":"section","href":"index.html#how-to-read-this","num":null,"sectionName":"Start","title":"Overview","heading":"How to read this","text":"How to read this The chapters are ordered, but modular. Open the sidebar on the left to jump around, or use the Next button at the bottom of every page for a linear path. Tap ⌘K (or / ) any time to search across every chapter and section. Keyboard shortcuts. J or → for next chapter, K or ← for previous.","snippet":"The chapters are ordered, but modular. Open the sidebar on the left to jump around, or use the Next button at the bottom of every page for a linear path. Tap ⌘K (or / ) any time to search across every chapter and section. Keyboard shortcuts. J or → for next chapter, K or ← for previous."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"01-what-is-emdash.html","num":"01","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"What is emdash?","text":"The open-source, TypeScript-based CMS that Cloudflare released as a successor to WordPress. emdash is published under the MIT license and currently sits in beta preview. It was announced in early 2026 on the Cloudflare blog under the title \"Introducing EmDash: a WordPress successor for the post-WordPress web.\"","snippet":"The open-source, TypeScript-based CMS that Cloudflare released as a successor to WordPress."},{"kind":"section","href":"01-what-is-emdash.html#the-thesis","num":"01","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"What is emdash?","heading":"The thesis","text":"The thesis \"EmDash is committed to building on what WordPress created: an open source publishing stack that anyone can install and use at little cost, while fixing the core problems that WordPress cannot solve.\" emdash is pitched as a respectful successor rather than a hostile replacement. It inherits WordPress's open-publishing philosophy and redesigns the execution model for a serverless, AI-native world.","snippet":"\"EmDash is committed to building on what WordPress created: an open source publishing stack that anyone can install and use at little cost, while fixing the core problems that WordPress cannot solve.\" emdash is pitched as a respectful successor rather than a hostile replacement. It inherits WordPress's open-publishing philosophy and redesigns the execution model for a serverless, AI-native world."},{"kind":"section","href":"01-what-is-emdash.html#the-four-problems-it-targets","num":"01","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"What is emdash?","heading":"The four problems it targets","text":"The four problems it targets 1. Plugin security 96% of WordPress security vulnerabilities come from plugins. In WordPress, a plugin gets unrestricted access to the database and filesystem — there's no isolation boundary. In emdash, every plugin runs in an isolated V8 sandbox and can only do what its manifest explicitly permits. 2. Marketplace lock-in WordPress plugins are GPL-licensed (forcing derivative licensing choices) and face a 2+ week review queue with 800+ plugins waiting. emdash is MIT, and plugin authors keep their own licensing. 3. Infrastructure waste WordPress needs always-on servers that can't scale to zero.","snippet":"1. Plugin security 96% of WordPress security vulnerabilities come from plugins. In WordPress, a plugin gets unrestricted access to the database and filesystem — there's no isolation boundary. In emdash, every plugin runs in an isolated V8 sandbox and can only do what its manifest explicitly permits. 2. Marketplace lock-in WordPress plugins are GPL-licensed (forcing derivative licensing choices) and face a 2+ week review queue with 800+ plugins waiting. emdash is MIT, and plugin authors keep their own licensing. 3. Infrastructure waste WordPress needs always-on servers that can't scale to zero."},{"kind":"section","href":"01-what-is-emdash.html#key-facts-at-a-glance","num":"01","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"What is emdash?","heading":"Key facts at a glance","text":"Key facts at a glance Attribute Value License MIT Language TypeScript (end to end) Frontend framework Astro 6 Admin UI React 19 Rich-text format Portable Text (structured JSON, not HTML) Database Cloudflare D1 — PostgreSQL, Turso/libSQL, local SQLite also supported Media storage Cloudflare R2 — S3-compatible and local filesystem also supported Sessions Cloudflare KV (or Redis / file-based) Runtime Cloudflare Workers (primary) or Node.js (fallback) Auth Passkeys first, OAuth / magic links as fallbacks Status Beta preview (as of early 2026) Note. The \"Cloudflare-first\" framing doesn't mean Cloudflare-locked. emdash s","snippet":"Attribute Value License MIT Language TypeScript (end to end) Frontend framework Astro 6 Admin UI React 19 Rich-text format Portable Text (structured JSON, not HTML) Database Cloudflare D1 — PostgreSQL, Turso/libSQL, local SQLite also supported Media storage Cloudflare R2 — S3-compatible and local filesystem also supported Sessions Cloudflare KV (or Redis / file-based) Runtime Cloudflare Workers (primary) or Node.js (fallback) Auth Passkeys first, OAuth / magic links as fallbacks Status Beta preview (as of early 2026) Note. The \"Cloudflare-first\" framing doesn't mean Cloudflare-locked. emdash s"},{"kind":"chapter","href":"02-how-emdash-works.html","num":"02","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"How emdash works","text":"The one architectural fact that makes everything else click: emdash is not a standalone application. It's an Astro integration. You install emdash into any Astro project. When you run that project, the integration:","snippet":"The one architectural fact that makes everything else click: emdash is not a standalone application. It's an Astro integration."},{"kind":"section","href":"02-how-emdash-works.html#the-picture","num":"02","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"How emdash works","heading":"The picture","text":"The picture ┌──────────────────────── Your Astro Site ─────────────────────────┐ │ │ │ src/pages/ ← your public routes │ │ index.astro │ │ posts/[slug].astro ← calls getEmDashCollection(\"post\") │ │ │ │ src/live.config.ts ← registers the emdash loader │ │ │ │ astro.config.mjs ← adds the emdash integration │ │ + @astrojs/cloudflare adapter │ └──────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┘ │ at build & runtime ▼ ┌─────────────────────── emdash integration ───────────────────────┐ │ │ │ /_emdash/admin React admin UI, passkey auth │ │ /_emdash/api/* Content, media, auth, setup endpoints │ ","snippet":"┌──────────────────────── Your Astro Site ─────────────────────────┐ │ │ │ src/pages/ ← your public routes │ │ index.astro │ │ posts/[slug].astro ← calls getEmDashCollection(\"post\") │ │ │ │ src/live.config.ts ← registers the emdash loader │ │ │ │ astro.config.mjs ← adds the emdash integration │ │ + @astrojs/cloudflare adapter │ └──────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┘ │ at build & runtime ▼ ┌─────────────────────── emdash integration ───────────────────────┐ │ │ │ /_emdash/admin React admin UI, passkey auth │ │ /_emdash/api/* Content, media, auth, setup endpoints │ "},{"kind":"section","href":"02-how-emdash-works.html#three-ideas-to-remember","num":"02","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"How emdash works","heading":"Three ideas to remember","text":"Three ideas to remember 1. Content lives in a relational DB, not in files Most Astro CMSes store content as markdown files in src/content/ . emdash is different. Your content is rows in D1 (or SQLite/Postgres), stored as Portable Text — a structured JSON format. The admin UI reads and writes those rows. Developers can still commit seed data ( seed/seed.json ), but the source of truth at runtime is the database. 2. Pages consume content through one live collection You don't call the usual Astro getCollection(\"posts\") . Instead you call getEmDashCollection(\"posts\") , which queries the database through emdash's loader. ","snippet":"1. Content lives in a relational DB, not in files Most Astro CMSes store content as markdown files in src/content/ . emdash is different. Your content is rows in D1 (or SQLite/Postgres), stored as Portable Text — a structured JSON format. The admin UI reads and writes those rows. Developers can still commit seed data ( seed/seed.json ), but the source of truth at runtime is the database. 2. Pages consume content through one live collection You don't call the usual Astro getCollection(\"posts\") . Instead you call getEmDashCollection(\"posts\") , which queries the database through emdash's loader. "},{"kind":"section","href":"02-how-emdash-works.html#the-five-files-that-shape-any-emdash-site","num":"02","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"How emdash works","heading":"The five files that shape any emdash site","text":"The five files that shape any emdash site Once these are in your head, everything else is decoration: File Role astro.config.mjs Registers the emdash integration and the Cloudflare adapter. src/live.config.ts Defines the _emdash live content collection. wrangler.jsonc Declares D1 / R2 / KV bindings. (Cloudflare variant only.) seed/seed.json Initial content loaded by emdash seed . src/pages/*.astro Your public UI; calls getEmDashCollection / getEmDashEntry .","snippet":"Once these are in your head, everything else is decoration: File Role astro.config.mjs Registers the emdash integration and the Cloudflare adapter. src/live.config.ts Defines the _emdash live content collection. wrangler.jsonc Declares D1 / R2 / KV bindings. (Cloudflare variant only.) seed/seed.json Initial content loaded by emdash seed . src/pages/*.astro Your public UI; calls getEmDashCollection / getEmDashEntry ."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","text":"emdash is Cloudflare-first. If you've never used Cloudflare's developer platform, this chapter is for you. If you have, skip to the next chapter. Go to dash.cloudflare.com and create an account. No credit card is required for the free tier, which covers everything needed to try emdash:","snippet":"emdash is Cloudflare-first. If you've never used Cloudflare's developer platform, this chapter is for you. If you have, skip to the next chapter."},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#sign-up","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"Sign up","text":"Sign up Go to dash.cloudflare.com and create an account. No credit card is required for the free tier, which covers everything needed to try emdash: Workers : 100,000 requests/day D1 : up to 10 databases, 500 MB each KV : 100k reads, 1k writes per day R2 : 10 GB storage, zero egress fees at every tier Plugins require the Paid plan. The only emdash feature that needs the $5/month Workers Paid plan is the sandboxed plugin system (it relies on Dynamic Workers / Worker Loader). Disable plugins and you stay on the free tier.","snippet":"Go to dash.cloudflare.com and create an account. No credit card is required for the free tier, which covers everything needed to try emdash: Workers : 100,000 requests/day D1 : up to 10 databases, 500 MB each KV : 100k reads, 1k writes per day R2 : 10 GB storage, zero egress fees at every tier Plugins require the Paid plan. The only emdash feature that needs the $5/month Workers Paid plan is the sandboxed plugin system (it relies on Dynamic Workers / Worker Loader). Disable plugins and you stay on the free tier."},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#cloudflare-workers","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"Cloudflare Workers","text":"Cloudflare Workers A Worker is a JavaScript / TypeScript function that runs on Cloudflare's global network. Unlike AWS Lambda (containers, 100–1000 ms cold starts), Workers run inside V8 isolates — the same lightweight sandbox Chrome uses for browser tabs. Cold start: under 5 ms. Hello world is a single file: export default { async fetch(request: Request, env: Env): Promise<Response> { return new Response(\"Hello from the edge!\"); } }; No Express, no framework. Request and Response are standard Web APIs.","snippet":"A Worker is a JavaScript / TypeScript function that runs on Cloudflare's global network. Unlike AWS Lambda (containers, 100–1000 ms cold starts), Workers run inside V8 isolates — the same lightweight sandbox Chrome uses for browser tabs. Cold start: under 5 ms. Hello world is a single file: export default { async fetch(request: Request, env: Env): Promise<Response> { return new Response(\"Hello from the edge!\"); } }; No Express, no framework. Request and Response are standard Web APIs."},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#the-wrangler-cli","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"The Wrangler CLI","text":"The Wrangler CLI Wrangler is how you build, run, and deploy Workers. It's an npm package: npm install -g wrangler wrangler login # opens a browser OAuth flow Commands you'll use constantly: Command What it does wrangler dev Local dev server (powered by workerd , the real runtime) wrangler deploy Pushes your Worker to Cloudflare's global network wrangler d1 create <name> Creates a D1 database and prints its ID wrangler r2 bucket create <name> Creates an R2 bucket wrangler kv namespace create <name> Creates a KV namespace wrangler secret put <KEY> Uploads an encrypted secret","snippet":"Wrangler is how you build, run, and deploy Workers. It's an npm package: npm install -g wrangler wrangler login # opens a browser OAuth flow Commands you'll use constantly: Command What it does wrangler dev Local dev server (powered by workerd , the real runtime) wrangler deploy Pushes your Worker to Cloudflare's global network wrangler d1 create <name> Creates a D1 database and prints its ID wrangler r2 bucket create <name> Creates an R2 bucket wrangler kv namespace create <name> Creates a KV namespace wrangler secret put <KEY> Uploads an encrypted secret"},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#wrangler-jsonc-the-project-config","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"wrangler.jsonc — the project config","text":"wrangler.jsonc — the project config Every Worker project has a wrangler.jsonc (or wrangler.toml ). JSONC is the newer, recommended form — it supports JSON Schema validation in editors. A minimal emdash site's config looks roughly like this: { \"name\": \"my-emdash-site\", \"main\": \"./dist/_worker.js/index.js\", \"compatibility_date\": \"2026-04-20\", \"compatibility_flags\": [\"nodejs_compat\"], \"assets\": { \"binding\": \"ASSETS\", \"directory\": \"./dist\" }, \"d1_databases\": [ { \"binding\": \"DB\", \"database_name\": \"my-emdash-db\", \"database_id\": \"<paste-id-here>\" } ], \"r2_buckets\": [ { \"binding\": \"MEDIA\", \"bucket_name\": \"my-emdash-media\" } ], \"kv_names","snippet":"Every Worker project has a wrangler.jsonc (or wrangler.toml ). JSONC is the newer, recommended form — it supports JSON Schema validation in editors. A minimal emdash site's config looks roughly like this: { \"name\": \"my-emdash-site\", \"main\": \"./dist/_worker.js/index.js\", \"compatibility_date\": \"2026-04-20\", \"compatibility_flags\": [\"nodejs_compat\"], \"assets\": { \"binding\": \"ASSETS\", \"directory\": \"./dist\" }, \"d1_databases\": [ { \"binding\": \"DB\", \"database_name\": \"my-emdash-db\", \"database_id\": \"<paste-id-here>\" } ], \"r2_buckets\": [ { \"binding\": \"MEDIA\", \"bucket_name\": \"my-emdash-media\" } ], \"kv_names"},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#bindings-the-single-biggest-concept","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"Bindings — the single biggest concept","text":"Bindings — the single biggest concept A binding is how your Worker accesses Cloudflare services. You declare the relationship in wrangler.jsonc , and at runtime your code receives a ready-to-use client on the env object: // env.DB → D1 database client // env.MEDIA → R2 bucket client // env.SESSIONS → KV namespace client There are no connection strings and no API keys in your code . The platform injects the credentials, and you can't accidentally leak them in a log.","snippet":"A binding is how your Worker accesses Cloudflare services. You declare the relationship in wrangler.jsonc , and at runtime your code receives a ready-to-use client on the env object: // env.DB → D1 database client // env.MEDIA → R2 bucket client // env.SESSIONS → KV namespace client There are no connection strings and no API keys in your code . The platform injects the credentials, and you can't accidentally leak them in a log."},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#the-three-storage-services-at-a-glance","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"The three storage services at a glance","text":"The three storage services at a glance Service What it is When to use D1 SQLite at the edge, with global read replicas Relational data — posts, users, comments. emdash's primary store. R2 S3-compatible object storage, no egress fees Files — images, video, uploads. emdash stores media here. KV Eventually-consistent key-value store Read-heavy, flat data — sessions, feature flags, config. Rule of thumb: D1 for rows, R2 for files, KV for tokens and small config.","snippet":"Service What it is When to use D1 SQLite at the edge, with global read replicas Relational data — posts, users, comments. emdash's primary store. R2 S3-compatible object storage, no egress fees Files — images, video, uploads. emdash stores media here. KV Eventually-consistent key-value store Read-heavy, flat data — sessions, feature flags, config. Rule of thumb: D1 for rows, R2 for files, KV for tokens and small config."},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#pages-vs-workers-the-2025-merge","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"Pages vs Workers — the 2025 merge","text":"Pages vs Workers — the 2025 merge Cloudflare used to have two products: Workers for logic and Pages for static sites. In 2025 they converged into \"Workers with static assets.\" One Worker can now both serve your static HTML and run your SSR code. emdash uses this model: your Astro site builds to dist/ , Wrangler uploads both the Worker script and the static assets in a single deploy.","snippet":"Cloudflare used to have two products: Workers for logic and Pages for static sites. In 2025 they converged into \"Workers with static assets.\" One Worker can now both serve your static HTML and run your SSR code. emdash uses this model: your Astro site builds to dist/ , Wrangler uploads both the Worker script and the static assets in a single deploy."},{"kind":"section","href":"03-cloudflare-primer.html#local-dev-and-miniflare","num":"03","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Cloudflare primer","heading":"Local dev and Miniflare","text":"Local dev and Miniflare wrangler dev runs your Worker locally using workerd — the exact same runtime Cloudflare uses in production. Local D1 becomes a local SQLite file, local R2 becomes a folder on disk, local KV is in-memory. You can develop fully offline, and behavior closely mirrors production. If you need to test against real production resources (e.g., a seeded D1 database), run wrangler dev --remote .","snippet":"wrangler dev runs your Worker locally using workerd — the exact same runtime Cloudflare uses in production. Local D1 becomes a local SQLite file, local R2 becomes a folder on disk, local KV is in-memory. You can develop fully offline, and behavior closely mirrors production. If you need to test against real production resources (e.g., a seeded D1 database), run wrangler dev --remote ."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"04-astro-primer.html","num":"04","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Astro primer","text":"Astro is the web framework under every emdash template. Here's what you need to know to read and modify them. Astro is a content-first framework with two big ideas:","snippet":"Astro is the web framework under every emdash template. Here's what you need to know to read and modify them."},{"kind":"section","href":"04-astro-primer.html#the-astro-idea","num":"04","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Astro primer","heading":"The Astro idea","text":"The Astro idea Astro is a content-first framework with two big ideas: Zero JS by default. Every component renders to plain HTML at build time. No client-side JavaScript ships unless you explicitly ask for it. Islands. You opt into interactivity per-component with client:* directives. <MyReactWidget /> {/* static — no JS */} <MyReactWidget client:load /> {/* hydrated immediately */} <MyReactWidget client:visible /> {/* hydrated when scrolled into view */} Astro is framework-agnostic: React, Vue, Svelte, Preact, Solid, and plain .astro components mix freely in one project.","snippet":"Astro is a content-first framework with two big ideas: Zero JS by default. Every component renders to plain HTML at build time. No client-side JavaScript ships unless you explicitly ask for it. Islands. You opt into interactivity per-component with client:* directives. <MyReactWidget /> {/* static — no JS */} <MyReactWidget client:load /> {/* hydrated immediately */} <MyReactWidget client:visible /> {/* hydrated when scrolled into view */} Astro is framework-agnostic: React, Vue, Svelte, Preact, Solid, and plain .astro components mix freely in one project."},{"kind":"section","href":"04-astro-primer.html#project-layout","num":"04","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Astro primer","heading":"Project layout","text":"Project layout my-site/ ├── src/ │ ├── pages/ # file-system routing — index.astro → / │ ├── layouts/ # wrapper components │ ├── components/ # reused building blocks │ └── live.config.ts # content collections (emdash wires up here) ├── public/ # static assets served as-is ├── astro.config.mjs # integrations, adapter, output mode └── package.json Everything under src/pages/ is a route. Nothing outside that folder is routed.","snippet":"my-site/ ├── src/ │ ├── pages/ # file-system routing — index.astro → / │ ├── layouts/ # wrapper components │ ├── components/ # reused building blocks │ └── live.config.ts # content collections (emdash wires up here) ├── public/ # static assets served as-is ├── astro.config.mjs # integrations, adapter, output mode └── package.json Everything under src/pages/ is a route. Nothing outside that folder is routed."},{"kind":"section","href":"04-astro-primer.html#output-modes","num":"04","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Astro primer","heading":"Output modes","text":"Output modes output Result 'static' (default) Pre-built HTML — no server 'server' A Worker + static assets — full SSR 'hybrid' Per-page opt-in All emdash templates use output: 'server' , because the admin panel and content API require server-side code.","snippet":"output Result 'static' (default) Pre-built HTML — no server 'server' A Worker + static assets — full SSR 'hybrid' Per-page opt-in All emdash templates use output: 'server' , because the admin panel and content API require server-side code."},{"kind":"section","href":"04-astro-primer.html#the-cloudflare-adapter","num":"04","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Astro primer","heading":"The Cloudflare adapter","text":"The Cloudflare adapter @astrojs/cloudflare is what makes Astro SSR run on Workers. Minimal config: // astro.config.mjs import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config'; import cloudflare from '@astrojs/cloudflare'; export default defineConfig({ output: 'server', adapter: cloudflare(), }); At runtime, the adapter exposes your Cloudflare bindings through Astro.locals.runtime : --- const { env } = Astro.locals.runtime; const post = await env.DB.prepare(\"SELECT * FROM posts WHERE slug = ?\") .bind(Astro.params.slug) .first(); --- <h1>{post.title}</h1>","snippet":"@astrojs/cloudflare is what makes Astro SSR run on Workers. Minimal config: // astro.config.mjs import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config'; import cloudflare from '@astrojs/cloudflare'; export default defineConfig({ output: 'server', adapter: cloudflare(), }); At runtime, the adapter exposes your Cloudflare bindings through Astro.locals.runtime : --- const { env } = Astro.locals.runtime; const post = await env.DB.prepare(\"SELECT * FROM posts WHERE slug = ?\") .bind(Astro.params.slug) .first(); --- <h1>{post.title}</h1>"},{"kind":"section","href":"04-astro-primer.html#where-emdash-plugs-in","num":"04","sectionName":"Foundations","title":"Astro primer","heading":"Where emdash plugs in","text":"Where emdash plugs in Two files. That's it. 1. astro.config.mjs — register the integration import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config'; import cloudflare from '@astrojs/cloudflare'; import emdash from 'emdash/astro'; import { cloudflareAdapter } from '@emdash-cms/cloudflare'; export default defineConfig({ output: 'server', adapter: cloudflare(), integrations: [ emdash({ adapter: cloudflareAdapter({ db: 'DB', // D1 binding name media: 'MEDIA', // R2 binding name sessions: 'SESSIONS' // KV binding name }), plugins: [], marketplaceUrl: 'https://marketplace.emdashcms.com', }), ], }); 2. src/live.config.ts — declare the","snippet":"Two files. That's it. 1. astro.config.mjs — register the integration import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config'; import cloudflare from '@astrojs/cloudflare'; import emdash from 'emdash/astro'; import { cloudflareAdapter } from '@emdash-cms/cloudflare'; export default defineConfig({ output: 'server', adapter: cloudflare(), integrations: [ emdash({ adapter: cloudflareAdapter({ db: 'DB', // D1 binding name media: 'MEDIA', // R2 binding name sessions: 'SESSIONS' // KV binding name }), plugins: [], marketplaceUrl: 'https://marketplace.emdashcms.com', }), ], }); 2. src/live.config.ts — declare the"},{"kind":"chapter","href":"05-getting-started.html","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","text":"Scaffold your first emdash site in under five minutes. You'll be asked:","snippet":"Scaffold your first emdash site in under five minutes."},{"kind":"section","href":"05-getting-started.html#prerequisites","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","heading":"Prerequisites","text":"Prerequisites Node.js 22+ pnpm 10+ — enable with corepack enable A Cloudflare account (free tier is fine) Wrangler — npm install -g wrangler && wrangler login","snippet":"Node.js 22+ pnpm 10+ — enable with corepack enable A Cloudflare account (free tier is fine) Wrangler — npm install -g wrangler && wrangler login"},{"kind":"section","href":"05-getting-started.html#1-create-a-project","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","heading":"1. Create a project","text":"1. Create a project npm create emdash@latest You'll be asked: A template — blog , marketing , portfolio , starter , or blank . A deployment target — node (local SQLite, for self-hosting) or cloudflare (D1 + R2 + KV). For this tutorial, pick blog + cloudflare .","snippet":"npm create emdash@latest You'll be asked: A template — blog , marketing , portfolio , starter , or blank . A deployment target — node (local SQLite, for self-hosting) or cloudflare (D1 + R2 + KV). For this tutorial, pick blog + cloudflare ."},{"kind":"section","href":"05-getting-started.html#2-bootstrap","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","heading":"2. Bootstrap","text":"2. Bootstrap cd my-site pnpm install pnpm bootstrap # runs: emdash init && emdash seed pnpm dev What just happened: emdash init creates the database schema and migrations. emdash seed loads starter content from seed/seed.json . pnpm dev starts Astro's dev server (using workerd on the Cloudflare variant).","snippet":"cd my-site pnpm install pnpm bootstrap # runs: emdash init && emdash seed pnpm dev What just happened: emdash init creates the database schema and migrations. emdash seed loads starter content from seed/seed.json . pnpm dev starts Astro's dev server (using workerd on the Cloudflare variant)."},{"kind":"section","href":"05-getting-started.html#3-open-the-admin","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","heading":"3. Open the admin","text":"3. Open the admin Visit http://localhost:4321/_emdash/admin . On first visit, a setup wizard creates an admin account via passkey. If you want to skip passkey setup during local dev, use the bypass URL: http://localhost:4321/_emdash/api/setup/dev-bypass?redirect=/_emdash/admin","snippet":"Visit http://localhost:4321/_emdash/admin . On first visit, a setup wizard creates an admin account via passkey. If you want to skip passkey setup during local dev, use the bypass URL: http://localhost:4321/_emdash/api/setup/dev-bypass?redirect=/_emdash/admin"},{"kind":"section","href":"05-getting-started.html#4-see-your-site","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","heading":"4. See your site","text":"4. See your site Your public site is at http://localhost:4321 . Edit a post in the admin, refresh the homepage, see the change. What's the _emdash prefix? All emdash admin and API routes live under /_emdash/ . This keeps them out of the way of your own routes — you can build a /admin page of your own without colliding.","snippet":"Your public site is at http://localhost:4321 . Edit a post in the admin, refresh the homepage, see the change. What's the _emdash prefix? All emdash admin and API routes live under /_emdash/ . This keeps them out of the way of your own routes — you can build a /admin page of your own without colliding."},{"kind":"section","href":"05-getting-started.html#what-a-first-session-looks-like","num":"05","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Getting started","heading":"What a first session looks like","text":"What a first session looks like Open src/pages/index.astro and change a heading. The browser hot-reloads. Go to the admin, edit a post title, hit save. Refresh the public page. Open astro.config.mjs and see the emdash integration registered. Open src/live.config.ts and see the _emdash live collection. Browse to /_emdash/admin/schemas and look at the default content types.","snippet":"Open src/pages/index.astro and change a heading. The browser hot-reloads. Go to the admin, edit a post title, hit save. Refresh the public page. Open astro.config.mjs and see the emdash integration registered. Open src/live.config.ts and see the _emdash live collection. Browse to /_emdash/admin/schemas and look at the default content types."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"06-template-tour.html","num":"06","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Template tour","text":"A tour of the five official emdash templates, what they ship, and how a page actually reads content. All templates ship in two flavors: a Node.js variant and a -cloudflare variant. They share this structure:","snippet":"A tour of the five official emdash templates, what they ship, and how a page actually reads content."},{"kind":"section","href":"06-template-tour.html#the-five-templates","num":"06","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Template tour","heading":"The five templates","text":"The five templates Template Best for Notable pages blog Full blog: search, RSS, categories, tags, dark mode posts/ , category/ , tag/ , search.astro , rss.xml.ts marketing Landing site: hero, pricing, FAQ, contact form index.astro , pricing.astro , contact.astro portfolio Creative showcase: project grid, case studies work/ , about.astro , contact.astro starter Minimal, unopinionated foundation index.astro , [slug].astro , posts/ blank Empty canvas — only wires emdash up just index.astro","snippet":"Template Best for Notable pages blog Full blog: search, RSS, categories, tags, dark mode posts/ , category/ , tag/ , search.astro , rss.xml.ts marketing Landing site: hero, pricing, FAQ, contact form index.astro , pricing.astro , contact.astro portfolio Creative showcase: project grid, case studies work/ , about.astro , contact.astro starter Minimal, unopinionated foundation index.astro , [slug].astro , posts/ blank Empty canvas — only wires emdash up just index.astro"},{"kind":"section","href":"06-template-tour.html#node-vs-cloudflare-variants","num":"06","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Template tour","heading":"Node vs Cloudflare variants","text":"Node vs Cloudflare variants Same templates, different infrastructure. The only differences: Concern Node variant Cloudflare variant Adapter @astrojs/node @astrojs/cloudflare Database better-sqlite3 → ./data.db D1 via DB binding Media local ./uploads/ R2 via MEDIA binding Deploy node ./dist/server/entry.mjs wrangler deploy Extra dep — @emdash-cms/cloudflare , @cloudflare/workers-types","snippet":"Same templates, different infrastructure. The only differences: Concern Node variant Cloudflare variant Adapter @astrojs/node @astrojs/cloudflare Database better-sqlite3 → ./data.db D1 via DB binding Media local ./uploads/ R2 via MEDIA binding Deploy node ./dist/server/entry.mjs wrangler deploy Extra dep — @emdash-cms/cloudflare , @cloudflare/workers-types"},{"kind":"section","href":"06-template-tour.html#a-real-page-walk-through","num":"06","sectionName":"Get started","title":"Template tour","heading":"A real page walk-through","text":"A real page walk-through Here's what a post page in the blog template actually looks like: --- // src/pages/posts/[slug].astro import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashEntry, getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export async function getStaticPaths() { const { entries: posts } = await getEmDashCollection('post'); return posts.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })); } const { slug } = Astro.params; const { entry: post } = await getEmDashEntry('post', slug); if (!post) return Astro.redirect('/404'); --- <BaseLayout title={post.data.title}> <article> <h1>{post.data.title}</h1> <time>{p","snippet":"Here's what a post page in the blog template actually looks like: --- // src/pages/posts/[slug].astro import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashEntry, getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export async function getStaticPaths() { const { entries: posts } = await getEmDashCollection('post'); return posts.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })); } const { slug } = Astro.params; const { entry: post } = await getEmDashEntry('post', slug); if (!post) return Astro.redirect('/404'); --- <BaseLayout title={post.data.title}> <article> <h1>{post.data.title}</h1> <time>{p"},{"kind":"chapter","href":"07-content-modeling.html","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","text":"Unlike most Astro CMSes, emdash doesn't hard-code content types in TypeScript. You define them through the admin UI, and emdash handles the DB, migrations, and types. emdash creates the DB tables and exposes the new type through the API automatically. No migration file to write, no CREATE TABLE to run.","snippet":"Unlike most Astro CMSes, emdash doesn't hard-code content types in TypeScript. You define them through the admin UI, and emdash handles the DB, migrations, and types."},{"kind":"section","href":"07-content-modeling.html#creating-a-content-type","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","heading":"Creating a content type","text":"Creating a content type Go to /_emdash/admin → Schemas → New Schema . Name it (e.g. product ). Add fields — each has a type (text, number, boolean, rich text, reference, image, etc.) and options (required, default, validation). Save. emdash creates the DB tables and exposes the new type through the API automatically. No migration file to write, no CREATE TABLE to run.","snippet":"Go to /_emdash/admin → Schemas → New Schema . Name it (e.g. product ). Add fields — each has a type (text, number, boolean, rich text, reference, image, etc.) and options (required, default, validation). Save. emdash creates the DB tables and exposes the new type through the API automatically. No migration file to write, no CREATE TABLE to run."},{"kind":"section","href":"07-content-modeling.html#regenerating-typescript-types","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","heading":"Regenerating TypeScript types","text":"Regenerating TypeScript types Whenever you change a schema, regenerate the type definitions so your editor stays in sync: npx emdash types After running this, getEmDashCollection('product') is fully typed, and autocomplete will show every field you defined.","snippet":"Whenever you change a schema, regenerate the type definitions so your editor stays in sync: npx emdash types After running this, getEmDashCollection('product') is fully typed, and autocomplete will show every field you defined."},{"kind":"section","href":"07-content-modeling.html#portable-text-the-rich-text-format","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","heading":"Portable Text: the rich-text format","text":"Portable Text: the rich-text format Rich-text fields store Portable Text — a structured JSON array, not HTML. That matters for three reasons: No broken HTML from a user paste. You can render the same content to different frontends (web, mobile, voice) from one source. You can traverse the tree and apply custom behavior — auto-linking mentions, stripping disallowed marks, translating inline. You usually don't interact with the raw JSON. The loader renders it to HTML for you. But when you need custom rendering, the tree is yours to walk.","snippet":"Rich-text fields store Portable Text — a structured JSON array, not HTML. That matters for three reasons: No broken HTML from a user paste. You can render the same content to different frontends (web, mobile, voice) from one source. You can traverse the tree and apply custom behavior — auto-linking mentions, stripping disallowed marks, translating inline. You usually don't interact with the raw JSON. The loader renders it to HTML for you. But when you need custom rendering, the tree is yours to walk."},{"kind":"section","href":"07-content-modeling.html#querying-content-from-your-pages","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","heading":"Querying content from your pages","text":"Querying content from your pages Top-level helpers you'll reach for most often: import { getEmDashCollection, getEmDashEntry, } from 'emdash'; // All entries of a type (destructure the result) const { entries: allPosts } = await getEmDashCollection('post'); // Filtered + paginated const { entries: published, nextCursor } = await getEmDashCollection('post', { status: 'published', orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, limit: 10, }); // One entry (returns { entry, error, isPreview, ... }) const { entry: post } = await getEmDashEntry('post', 'my-slug'); Return shapes. getEmDashCollection returns { entries, error, cacheHint, nextCurso","snippet":"Top-level helpers you'll reach for most often: import { getEmDashCollection, getEmDashEntry, } from 'emdash'; // All entries of a type (destructure the result) const { entries: allPosts } = await getEmDashCollection('post'); // Filtered + paginated const { entries: published, nextCursor } = await getEmDashCollection('post', { status: 'published', orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, limit: 10, }); // One entry (returns { entry, error, isPreview, ... }) const { entry: post } = await getEmDashEntry('post', 'my-slug'); Return shapes. getEmDashCollection returns { entries, error, cacheHint, nextCurso"},{"kind":"section","href":"07-content-modeling.html#seed-data-vs-live-content","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","heading":"Seed data vs. live content","text":"Seed data vs. live content Each template ships a seed/seed.json that gets loaded by emdash seed . Treat it as initial content , not the source of truth: On first bootstrap, seed data populates the database so your site has something to render. After that, the database is the source of truth . Edits in the admin go to the DB, not to seed.json . If you re-run emdash seed , it re-imports the seed (behavior depends on the template — some idempotently upsert, some reset). A workflow that scales. Keep seed/seed.json under version control as canonical \"example content\" for new contributors, and let the production DB diverge fr","snippet":"Each template ships a seed/seed.json that gets loaded by emdash seed . Treat it as initial content , not the source of truth: On first bootstrap, seed data populates the database so your site has something to render. After that, the database is the source of truth . Edits in the admin go to the DB, not to seed.json . If you re-run emdash seed , it re-imports the seed (behavior depends on the template — some idempotently upsert, some reset). A workflow that scales. Keep seed/seed.json under version control as canonical \"example content\" for new contributors, and let the production DB diverge fr"},{"kind":"section","href":"07-content-modeling.html#relationships-between-types","num":"07","sectionName":"Build","title":"Content modeling","heading":"Relationships between types","text":"Relationships between types Fields of type reference link one content type to another (e.g. a post references a category ). When you query a post, its references are resolved automatically, so you can access post.data.category.name without a second query.","snippet":"Fields of type reference link one content type to another (e.g. a post references a category ). When you query a post, its references are resolved automatically, so you can access post.data.category.name without a second query."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"08-adding-pages.html","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","text":"Three common cases: a static page, a dynamic page driven by content, and a page that shows a filtered list. All three follow the same Astro routing rules. Every file in src/pages/ becomes a route. Nothing else is a route. File name → URL mapping:","snippet":"Three common cases: a static page, a dynamic page driven by content, and a page that shows a filtered list. All three follow the same Astro routing rules."},{"kind":"section","href":"08-adding-pages.html#the-one-rule-of-astro-routing","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","heading":"The one rule of Astro routing","text":"The one rule of Astro routing Every file in src/pages/ becomes a route. Nothing else is a route. File name → URL mapping: File URL src/pages/index.astro / src/pages/about.astro /about src/pages/blog/index.astro /blog src/pages/posts/[slug].astro /posts/:slug (dynamic) src/pages/rss.xml.ts /rss.xml (endpoint)","snippet":"Every file in src/pages/ becomes a route. Nothing else is a route. File name → URL mapping: File URL src/pages/index.astro / src/pages/about.astro /about src/pages/blog/index.astro /blog src/pages/posts/[slug].astro /posts/:slug (dynamic) src/pages/rss.xml.ts /rss.xml (endpoint)"},{"kind":"section","href":"08-adding-pages.html#tutorial-1-add-a-static-about-page","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","heading":"Tutorial 1 — add a static \"About\" page","text":"Tutorial 1 — add a static \"About\" page We'll use the BaseLayout that ships with every template so the new page picks up the header, footer, and global styles for free. Create the file // src/pages/about.astro --- import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; --- <BaseLayout title=\"About us\" description=\"Who we are and what we do.\"> <section class=\"prose\"> <h1>About us</h1> <p>We build tools for the web.</p> </section> </BaseLayout> Verify With pnpm dev running, open http://localhost:4321/about . The page renders; HMR means no restart needed. Link to it from the nav Open src/components/Header.astro (or whichever file owns yo","snippet":"We'll use the BaseLayout that ships with every template so the new page picks up the header, footer, and global styles for free. Create the file // src/pages/about.astro --- import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; --- <BaseLayout title=\"About us\" description=\"Who we are and what we do.\"> <section class=\"prose\"> <h1>About us</h1> <p>We build tools for the web.</p> </section> </BaseLayout> Verify With pnpm dev running, open http://localhost:4321/about . The page renders; HMR means no restart needed. Link to it from the nav Open src/components/Header.astro (or whichever file owns yo"},{"kind":"section","href":"08-adding-pages.html#tutorial-2-add-a-dynamic-page-from-a-content-type","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","heading":"Tutorial 2 — add a dynamic page from a content type","text":"Tutorial 2 — add a dynamic page from a content type Your admin has a post content type. We'll build /posts/:slug pages if the template doesn't have them, or study how the template already does it. Create the dynamic route // src/pages/posts/[slug].astro --- import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashEntry, getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export async function getStaticPaths() { const { entries: posts } = await getEmDashCollection('post'); return posts.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })); } const { slug } = Astro.params; const { entry: post } = await getEmDashEntry('post', slug); if (!post) return Astro.","snippet":"Your admin has a post content type. We'll build /posts/:slug pages if the template doesn't have them, or study how the template already does it. Create the dynamic route // src/pages/posts/[slug].astro --- import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashEntry, getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export async function getStaticPaths() { const { entries: posts } = await getEmDashCollection('post'); return posts.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })); } const { slug } = Astro.params; const { entry: post } = await getEmDashEntry('post', slug); if (!post) return Astro."},{"kind":"section","href":"08-adding-pages.html#tutorial-3-add-a-filtered-index-page","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","heading":"Tutorial 3 — add a filtered index page","text":"Tutorial 3 — add a filtered index page Build a page that only shows published posts from the last 30 days. // src/pages/recent.astro --- import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; const thirtyDaysAgo = new Date(); thirtyDaysAgo.setDate(thirtyDaysAgo.getDate() - 30); const { entries: recent } = await getEmDashCollection('post', { status: 'published', where: { publishedAt: { gte: thirtyDaysAgo.toISOString() } }, orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, limit: 20, }); --- <BaseLayout title=\"Recent posts\"> <h1>Recent posts</h1> <ul> {recent.map(p => ( <li> <a href={`/posts/${p.slug}`}>{","snippet":"Build a page that only shows published posts from the last 30 days. // src/pages/recent.astro --- import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; const thirtyDaysAgo = new Date(); thirtyDaysAgo.setDate(thirtyDaysAgo.getDate() - 30); const { entries: recent } = await getEmDashCollection('post', { status: 'published', where: { publishedAt: { gte: thirtyDaysAgo.toISOString() } }, orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, limit: 20, }); --- <BaseLayout title=\"Recent posts\"> <h1>Recent posts</h1> <ul> {recent.map(p => ( <li> <a href={`/posts/${p.slug}`}>{"},{"kind":"section","href":"08-adding-pages.html#endpoints-json-rss-sitemaps","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","heading":"Endpoints: JSON, RSS, sitemaps","text":"Endpoints: JSON, RSS, sitemaps Any .ts or .js file in src/pages/ becomes an HTTP endpoint. Great for RSS feeds, JSON APIs, and sitemaps. // src/pages/posts.json.ts import type { APIRoute } from 'astro'; import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export const GET: APIRoute = async () => { const { entries: posts } = await getEmDashCollection('post', { status: 'published', }); return new Response( JSON.stringify(posts.map(p => ({ slug: p.slug, title: p.data.title, publishedAt: p.data.publishedAt, }))), { headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } } ); }; Now GET /posts.json returns the list.","snippet":"Any .ts or .js file in src/pages/ becomes an HTTP endpoint. Great for RSS feeds, JSON APIs, and sitemaps. // src/pages/posts.json.ts import type { APIRoute } from 'astro'; import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export const GET: APIRoute = async () => { const { entries: posts } = await getEmDashCollection('post', { status: 'published', }); return new Response( JSON.stringify(posts.map(p => ({ slug: p.slug, title: p.data.title, publishedAt: p.data.publishedAt, }))), { headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } } ); }; Now GET /posts.json returns the list."},{"kind":"section","href":"08-adding-pages.html#cheat-sheet","num":"08","sectionName":"Build","title":"Adding pages","heading":"Cheat sheet","text":"Cheat sheet I want to... Create this file Add a static page src/pages/<name>.astro Add a dynamic page keyed by slug src/pages/<type>/[slug].astro Add a nested section src/pages/<section>/index.astro Return JSON/XML from a URL src/pages/<name>.json.ts (or .xml.ts ) Add a 404 src/pages/404.astro (ships in every template)","snippet":"I want to... Create this file Add a static page src/pages/<name>.astro Add a dynamic page keyed by slug src/pages/<type>/[slug].astro Add a nested section src/pages/<section>/index.astro Return JSON/XML from a URL src/pages/<name>.json.ts (or .xml.ts ) Add a 404 src/pages/404.astro (ships in every template)"},{"kind":"chapter","href":"09-customizing-templates.html","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","text":"Templates are not magic — they're just Astro projects. Anything you'd change in a regular Astro site, you can change here. This chapter walks through the five most common customizations. Templates expose design tokens as CSS custom properties. Open src/styles/global.css :","snippet":"Templates are not magic — they're just Astro projects. Anything you'd change in a regular Astro site, you can change here. This chapter walks through the five most common customizations."},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#the-four-places-you-ll-edit","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"The four places you'll edit","text":"The four places you'll edit To change... Edit... Site-wide colors, fonts, spacing src/styles/global.css Header, footer, meta tags, wrappers src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro Reusable UI pieces (cards, buttons) src/components/*.astro Site name, default author, SEO defaults src/config.ts (templates vary)","snippet":"To change... Edit... Site-wide colors, fonts, spacing src/styles/global.css Header, footer, meta tags, wrappers src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro Reusable UI pieces (cards, buttons) src/components/*.astro Site name, default author, SEO defaults src/config.ts (templates vary)"},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#tutorial-1-change-brand-colors-and-fonts","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"Tutorial 1 — change brand colors and fonts","text":"Tutorial 1 — change brand colors and fonts Templates expose design tokens as CSS custom properties. Open src/styles/global.css : :root { --color-bg: #ffffff; --color-text: #111827; --color-accent: #2563eb; /* ← change me */ --font-sans: \"Inter\", system-ui, sans-serif; --font-serif: \"Source Serif Pro\", Georgia, serif; } [data-theme=\"dark\"] { --color-bg: #0b0d10; --color-text: #e6edf3; --color-accent: #79c0ff; } Change --color-accent , save, and the whole site reflows in milliseconds. The accent variable is referenced from buttons, links, and focus states. Swap the font Three steps: Pick a font on Google Fonts or self-host from public/fo","snippet":"Templates expose design tokens as CSS custom properties. Open src/styles/global.css : :root { --color-bg: #ffffff; --color-text: #111827; --color-accent: #2563eb; /* ← change me */ --font-sans: \"Inter\", system-ui, sans-serif; --font-serif: \"Source Serif Pro\", Georgia, serif; } [data-theme=\"dark\"] { --color-bg: #0b0d10; --color-text: #e6edf3; --color-accent: #79c0ff; } Change --color-accent , save, and the whole site reflows in milliseconds. The accent variable is referenced from buttons, links, and focus states. Swap the font Three steps: Pick a font on Google Fonts or self-host from public/fo"},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#tutorial-2-edit-the-base-layout","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"Tutorial 2 — edit the base layout","text":"Tutorial 2 — edit the base layout BaseLayout.astro is the wrapper every page uses. It owns the <html> , <head> , <Header> , <main> , and <Footer> . Here's a typical shape: --- // src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro import Header from '../components/Header.astro'; import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'; import '../styles/global.css'; interface Props { title: string; description?: string; } const { title, description } = Astro.props; --- <html lang=\"en\"> <head> <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" /> <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" /> <title>{title}</title> {description && <meta name=\"description\" content=","snippet":"BaseLayout.astro is the wrapper every page uses. It owns the <html> , <head> , <Header> , <main> , and <Footer> . Here's a typical shape: --- // src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro import Header from '../components/Header.astro'; import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'; import '../styles/global.css'; interface Props { title: string; description?: string; } const { title, description } = Astro.props; --- <html lang=\"en\"> <head> <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" /> <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" /> <title>{title}</title> {description && <meta name=\"description\" content="},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#tutorial-3-add-or-modify-a-component","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"Tutorial 3 — add or modify a component","text":"Tutorial 3 — add or modify a component Components live in src/components/ . Here's a typed PostCard.astro you might drop in: --- // src/components/PostCard.astro interface Props { slug: string; title: string; excerpt?: string; publishedAt?: string; } const { slug, title, excerpt, publishedAt } = Astro.props; --- <a class=\"post-card\" href={`/posts/${slug}`}> <h3>{title}</h3> {excerpt && <p>{excerpt}</p>} {publishedAt && ( <time datetime={publishedAt}> {new Date(publishedAt).toLocaleDateString()} </time> )} </a> <style> .post-card { display: block; padding: 1rem 1.25rem; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: 8px; colo","snippet":"Components live in src/components/ . Here's a typed PostCard.astro you might drop in: --- // src/components/PostCard.astro interface Props { slug: string; title: string; excerpt?: string; publishedAt?: string; } const { slug, title, excerpt, publishedAt } = Astro.props; --- <a class=\"post-card\" href={`/posts/${slug}`}> <h3>{title}</h3> {excerpt && <p>{excerpt}</p>} {publishedAt && ( <time datetime={publishedAt}> {new Date(publishedAt).toLocaleDateString()} </time> )} </a> <style> .post-card { display: block; padding: 1rem 1.25rem; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: 8px; colo"},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#tutorial-4-add-an-interactive-react-island","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"Tutorial 4 — add an interactive React island","text":"Tutorial 4 — add an interactive React island Every template installs @astrojs/react already. Drop a React component in and hydrate it with client:* : // src/components/Counter.tsx import { useState } from 'react'; export default function Counter() { const [n, setN] = useState(0); return <button onClick={() => setN(n + 1)}>Clicked {n}</button>; } // In any .astro page --- import Counter from '../components/Counter.tsx'; --- <Counter client:load /> Everything else on the page remains zero-JS; only the Counter ships React.","snippet":"Every template installs @astrojs/react already. Drop a React component in and hydrate it with client:* : // src/components/Counter.tsx import { useState } from 'react'; export default function Counter() { const [n, setN] = useState(0); return <button onClick={() => setN(n + 1)}>Clicked {n}</button>; } // In any .astro page --- import Counter from '../components/Counter.tsx'; --- <Counter client:load /> Everything else on the page remains zero-JS; only the Counter ships React."},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#tutorial-5-update-seed-content","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"Tutorial 5 — update seed content","text":"Tutorial 5 — update seed content seed/seed.json is the starter content loaded by emdash seed . Edit it to change what a fresh clone starts with: { \"posts\": [ { \"slug\": \"welcome\", \"title\": \"Welcome to our blog\", \"publishedAt\": \"2026-04-20T10:00:00Z\", \"status\": \"published\", \"body\": [ /* Portable Text blocks */ ] } ], \"categories\": [ { \"slug\": \"general\", \"name\": \"General\" } ] } After editing, reseed: pnpm emdash seed Seed is not a sync. Editing seed.json does not push those changes into an already-populated database. Behavior on re-seed depends on the template: some upsert, some require --reset . Check your template's script.","snippet":"seed/seed.json is the starter content loaded by emdash seed . Edit it to change what a fresh clone starts with: { \"posts\": [ { \"slug\": \"welcome\", \"title\": \"Welcome to our blog\", \"publishedAt\": \"2026-04-20T10:00:00Z\", \"status\": \"published\", \"body\": [ /* Portable Text blocks */ ] } ], \"categories\": [ { \"slug\": \"general\", \"name\": \"General\" } ] } After editing, reseed: pnpm emdash seed Seed is not a sync. Editing seed.json does not push those changes into an already-populated database. Behavior on re-seed depends on the template: some upsert, some require --reset . Check your template's script."},{"kind":"section","href":"09-customizing-templates.html#where-not-to-customize","num":"09","sectionName":"Build","title":"Customizing templates","heading":"Where not to customize","text":"Where not to customize Don't edit files under node_modules/emdash/ or node_modules/@emdash-cms/ . Those are the CMS itself. If you need to change admin behavior, write a plugin . If you need to change the admin UI's look, the team is working on theming hooks — track the GitHub repo for updates.","snippet":"Don't edit files under node_modules/emdash/ or node_modules/@emdash-cms/ . Those are the CMS itself. If you need to change admin behavior, write a plugin . If you need to change the admin UI's look, the team is working on theming hooks — track the GitHub repo for updates."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"10-building-content-type.html","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","text":"Walk through the full loop — schema, types, list page, detail page, navigation, seed — by adding a project content type to the blog template. emdash has now created the DB tables and exposed a new project type through the API.","snippet":"Walk through the full loop — schema, types, list page, detail page, navigation, seed — by adding a project content type to the blog template."},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-1-define-the-schema-in-the-admin","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 1 — Define the schema in the admin","text":"Step 1 — Define the schema in the admin Start the dev server: pnpm dev . Open http://localhost:4321/_emdash/admin . Go to Schemas → New Schema . Name: project . Label: Projects . Add fields: Field Type Required Notes title Text Yes The project name slug Slug Yes Auto-derived from title summary Text (long) Yes One-line pitch for listing pages cover Image No Hero image body Rich text Yes Portable Text tags Array of Text No For filtering url URL No Link to the live project publishedAt DateTime Yes For sorting Save. emdash has now created the DB tables and exposed a new project type through the API.","snippet":"Start the dev server: pnpm dev . Open http://localhost:4321/_emdash/admin . Go to Schemas → New Schema . Name: project . Label: Projects . Add fields: Field Type Required Notes title Text Yes The project name slug Slug Yes Auto-derived from title summary Text (long) Yes One-line pitch for listing pages cover Image No Hero image body Rich text Yes Portable Text tags Array of Text No For filtering url URL No Link to the live project publishedAt DateTime Yes For sorting Save. emdash has now created the DB tables and exposed a new project type through the API."},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-2-regenerate-types","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 2 — Regenerate types","text":"Step 2 — Regenerate types In a second terminal: npx emdash types This writes TypeScript types for project so getEmDashCollection('project') gets full autocomplete.","snippet":"In a second terminal: npx emdash types This writes TypeScript types for project so getEmDashCollection('project') gets full autocomplete."},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-3-create-a-few-entries","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 3 — Create a few entries","text":"Step 3 — Create a few entries Back in the admin: Projects → New . Fill in a title, summary, upload a cover, write the body, add tags, set a date. Save as Published . Create 2&ndash;3 so your list page has something to render.","snippet":"Back in the admin: Projects → New . Fill in a title, summary, upload a cover, write the body, add tags, set a date. Save as Published . Create 2&ndash;3 so your list page has something to render."},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-4-build-the-list-page","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 4 — Build the list page","text":"Step 4 — Build the list page Create src/pages/projects/index.astro : --- import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; const { entries: projects } = await getEmDashCollection('project', { status: 'published', orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, }); --- <BaseLayout title=\"Projects\" description=\"Things we've shipped.\" > <section class=\"wrap\"> <h1>Projects</h1> <div class=\"grid\"> {projects.map(p => ( <a class=\"card\" href={`/projects/${p.slug}`}> {p.data.cover && ( <img src={p.data.cover.url} alt={p.data.title} loading=\"lazy\" /> )} <h2>{p.data.title}</h2> <p>{p.data.summa","snippet":"Create src/pages/projects/index.astro : --- import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; const { entries: projects } = await getEmDashCollection('project', { status: 'published', orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, }); --- <BaseLayout title=\"Projects\" description=\"Things we've shipped.\" > <section class=\"wrap\"> <h1>Projects</h1> <div class=\"grid\"> {projects.map(p => ( <a class=\"card\" href={`/projects/${p.slug}`}> {p.data.cover && ( <img src={p.data.cover.url} alt={p.data.title} loading=\"lazy\" /> )} <h2>{p.data.title}</h2> <p>{p.data.summa"},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-5-build-the-detail-page","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 5 — Build the detail page","text":"Step 5 — Build the detail page Create src/pages/projects/[slug].astro : --- import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashEntry, getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export async function getStaticPaths() { const { entries: projects } = await getEmDashCollection('project', { status: 'published', }); return projects.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })); } const { slug } = Astro.params; const { entry: project } = await getEmDashEntry('project', slug); if (!project) return Astro.redirect('/404'); --- <BaseLayout title={project.data.title} description={project.data.summary}> <article class=\"pros","snippet":"Create src/pages/projects/[slug].astro : --- import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'; import { getEmDashEntry, getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; export async function getStaticPaths() { const { entries: projects } = await getEmDashCollection('project', { status: 'published', }); return projects.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })); } const { slug } = Astro.params; const { entry: project } = await getEmDashEntry('project', slug); if (!project) return Astro.redirect('/404'); --- <BaseLayout title={project.data.title} description={project.data.summary}> <article class=\"pros"},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-6-add-it-to-the-nav","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 6 — Add it to the nav","text":"Step 6 — Add it to the nav Open src/components/Header.astro : <nav> <a href=\"/\">Home</a> <a href=\"/posts\">Posts</a> <a href=\"/projects\">Projects</a> {/* ← new */} <a href=\"/about\">About</a> </nav>","snippet":"Open src/components/Header.astro : <nav> <a href=\"/\">Home</a> <a href=\"/posts\">Posts</a> <a href=\"/projects\">Projects</a> {/* ← new */} <a href=\"/about\">About</a> </nav>"},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-7-optional-seed-it-for-new-contributors","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 7 (optional) — Seed it for new contributors","text":"Step 7 (optional) — Seed it for new contributors Add a projects array to seed/seed.json so teammates who clone the repo see sample data on first bootstrap: { \"posts\": [ /* ... existing ... */ ], \"projects\": [ { \"slug\": \"orbit\", \"title\": \"Orbit\", \"summary\": \"A tiny scheduler for Cloudflare Cron Triggers.\", \"publishedAt\": \"2026-03-01T00:00:00Z\", \"status\": \"published\", \"tags\": [\"tool\", \"cloudflare\"], \"body\": [ { \"_type\": \"block\", \"children\": [ { \"_type\": \"span\", \"text\": \"Orbit is a zero-config...\" } ] } ] } ] }","snippet":"Add a projects array to seed/seed.json so teammates who clone the repo see sample data on first bootstrap: { \"posts\": [ /* ... existing ... */ ], \"projects\": [ { \"slug\": \"orbit\", \"title\": \"Orbit\", \"summary\": \"A tiny scheduler for Cloudflare Cron Triggers.\", \"publishedAt\": \"2026-03-01T00:00:00Z\", \"status\": \"published\", \"tags\": [\"tool\", \"cloudflare\"], \"body\": [ { \"_type\": \"block\", \"children\": [ { \"_type\": \"span\", \"text\": \"Orbit is a zero-config...\" } ] } ] } ] }"},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#step-8-deploy","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"Step 8 — Deploy","text":"Step 8 — Deploy Push your code. Run pnpm deploy . Apply schema changes to production D1 (your template's remote migration script — see chapter 11 ). Visit the live /projects .","snippet":"Push your code. Run pnpm deploy . Apply schema changes to production D1 (your template's remote migration script — see chapter 11 ). Visit the live /projects ."},{"kind":"section","href":"10-building-content-type.html#what-you-just-practiced","num":"10","sectionName":"Build","title":"Building for a new content type","heading":"What you just practiced","text":"What you just practiced Defining a schema without writing migrations. Getting fully-typed content with emdash types . Using getEmDashCollection with filters, sorts, and limits. Building list + detail pages with Astro file routing. Committing portable sample content to seed.json . Repeat this loop for every new content type your site needs.","snippet":"Defining a schema without writing migrations. Getting fully-typed content with emdash types . Using getEmDashCollection with filters, sorts, and limits. Building list + detail pages with Astro file routing. Committing portable sample content to seed.json . Repeat this loop for every new content type your site needs."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"11-deploying.html","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","text":"From wrangler login to a live URL. Assumes you chose the -cloudflare variant of a template. You need a D1 database, an R2 bucket, and a KV namespace.","snippet":"From wrangler login to a live URL. Assumes you chose the -cloudflare variant of a template."},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#step-1-create-the-cloudflare-resources","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"Step 1 — Create the Cloudflare resources","text":"Step 1 — Create the Cloudflare resources You need a D1 database, an R2 bucket, and a KV namespace. # From inside your project directory wrangler d1 create my-emdash-db # → copy the database_id it prints wrangler r2 bucket create my-emdash-media wrangler kv namespace create SESSIONS # → copy the id it prints","snippet":"You need a D1 database, an R2 bucket, and a KV namespace. # From inside your project directory wrangler d1 create my-emdash-db # → copy the database_id it prints wrangler r2 bucket create my-emdash-media wrangler kv namespace create SESSIONS # → copy the id it prints"},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#step-2-wire-up-wrangler-jsonc","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"Step 2 — Wire up wrangler.jsonc","text":"Step 2 — Wire up wrangler.jsonc Open wrangler.jsonc in your project and paste the IDs into the respective bindings: { \"name\": \"my-emdash-site\", \"main\": \"./dist/_worker.js/index.js\", \"compatibility_date\": \"2026-04-20\", \"compatibility_flags\": [\"nodejs_compat\"], \"assets\": { \"binding\": \"ASSETS\", \"directory\": \"./dist\" }, \"d1_databases\": [ { \"binding\": \"DB\", \"database_name\": \"my-emdash-db\", \"database_id\": \"<paste-d1-id>\" } ], \"r2_buckets\": [ { \"binding\": \"MEDIA\", \"bucket_name\": \"my-emdash-media\" } ], \"kv_namespaces\": [ { \"binding\": \"SESSIONS\", \"id\": \"<paste-kv-id>\" } ] // If you are on the free plan, remove or comment out any // \"","snippet":"Open wrangler.jsonc in your project and paste the IDs into the respective bindings: { \"name\": \"my-emdash-site\", \"main\": \"./dist/_worker.js/index.js\", \"compatibility_date\": \"2026-04-20\", \"compatibility_flags\": [\"nodejs_compat\"], \"assets\": { \"binding\": \"ASSETS\", \"directory\": \"./dist\" }, \"d1_databases\": [ { \"binding\": \"DB\", \"database_name\": \"my-emdash-db\", \"database_id\": \"<paste-d1-id>\" } ], \"r2_buckets\": [ { \"binding\": \"MEDIA\", \"bucket_name\": \"my-emdash-media\" } ], \"kv_namespaces\": [ { \"binding\": \"SESSIONS\", \"id\": \"<paste-kv-id>\" } ] // If you are on the free plan, remove or comment out any // \""},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#step-3-run-migrations-against-production-d1","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"Step 3 — Run migrations against production D1","text":"Step 3 — Run migrations against production D1 Your template's package.json includes scripts for preparing remote D1. The exact script name can vary ( pnpm db:migrate , pnpm emdash:init:remote , etc.) — check your template's package.json . The general pattern is: # Apply the emdash schema to your remote D1 database pnpm bootstrap --remote # template-specific: check package.json scripts # Optionally seed production with starter content pnpm seed --remote # same caveat Under the hood, these commands use Wrangler's D1 query API ( wrangler d1 execute DB --remote --file=... ) to run the generated migrations against your actual Cloudflare databa","snippet":"Your template's package.json includes scripts for preparing remote D1. The exact script name can vary ( pnpm db:migrate , pnpm emdash:init:remote , etc.) — check your template's package.json . The general pattern is: # Apply the emdash schema to your remote D1 database pnpm bootstrap --remote # template-specific: check package.json scripts # Optionally seed production with starter content pnpm seed --remote # same caveat Under the hood, these commands use Wrangler's D1 query API ( wrangler d1 execute DB --remote --file=... ) to run the generated migrations against your actual Cloudflare databa"},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#step-4-deploy","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"Step 4 — Deploy","text":"Step 4 — Deploy pnpm deploy This runs astro build and then wrangler deploy . Within seconds your site is live on *.workers.dev (or your custom domain if configured). Wrangler prints the URL.","snippet":"pnpm deploy This runs astro build and then wrangler deploy . Within seconds your site is live on *.workers.dev (or your custom domain if configured). Wrangler prints the URL."},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#step-5-set-up-the-production-admin","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"Step 5 — Set up the production admin","text":"Step 5 — Set up the production admin Visit https://<your-worker>.workers.dev/_emdash/admin . The setup wizard runs once, you register a passkey, and you're the admin.","snippet":"Visit https://<your-worker>.workers.dev/_emdash/admin . The setup wizard runs once, you register a passkey, and you're the admin."},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#step-6-optional-protect-the-admin-with-cloudflare-access","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"Step 6 (optional) — Protect the admin with Cloudflare Access","text":"Step 6 (optional) — Protect the admin with Cloudflare Access If you want zero-trust SSO on top of emdash's built-in auth: In the Cloudflare dashboard, go to Zero Trust → Access → Applications → Add application . Create a Self-hosted application with path /_emdash/* . Add a policy, e.g. \"Emails matching *@yourcompany.com \" . Pick an identity provider (GitHub, Google, one-time PIN via email). Now only authorized users even reach the admin URL — requests are rejected at Cloudflare's edge before touching your Worker.","snippet":"If you want zero-trust SSO on top of emdash's built-in auth: In the Cloudflare dashboard, go to Zero Trust → Access → Applications → Add application . Create a Self-hosted application with path /_emdash/* . Add a policy, e.g. \"Emails matching *@yourcompany.com \" . Pick an identity provider (GitHub, Google, one-time PIN via email). Now only authorized users even reach the admin URL — requests are rejected at Cloudflare's edge before touching your Worker."},{"kind":"section","href":"11-deploying.html#the-feedback-loop","num":"11","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Deploying to Cloudflare","heading":"The feedback loop","text":"The feedback loop Cycle Command Target Fast dev pnpm dev Local workerd + local SQLite file Production parity pnpm dev --remote Local code, real D1/R2/KV Ship pnpm deploy Cloudflare global network Custom domains. In the Cloudflare dashboard, open your Worker → Settings → Triggers → Custom Domains . Add your domain; Cloudflare issues the certificate automatically if the domain is managed by Cloudflare DNS.","snippet":"Cycle Command Target Fast dev pnpm dev Local workerd + local SQLite file Production parity pnpm dev --remote Local code, real D1/R2/KV Ship pnpm deploy Cloudflare global network Custom domains. In the Cloudflare dashboard, open your Worker → Settings → Triggers → Custom Domains . Add your domain; Cloudflare issues the certificate automatically if the domain is managed by Cloudflare DNS."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"12-plugins.html","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","text":"emdash's flagship architectural choice — sandboxed plugins — and how the MCP server turns the CMS into an AI-native authoring surface. Every plugin runs inside its own V8 isolate (a Dynamic Worker ). A plugin declares a capability manifest up front:","snippet":"emdash's flagship architectural choice — sandboxed plugins — and how the MCP server turns the CMS into an AI-native authoring surface."},{"kind":"section","href":"12-plugins.html#the-sandbox-model","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","heading":"The sandbox model","text":"The sandbox model Every plugin runs inside its own V8 isolate (a Dynamic Worker ). A plugin declares a capability manifest up front: { \"name\": \"my-notifier\", \"capabilities\": [ \"read:content.post\", \"network:send\", \"email:send\" ] } The runtime enforces those capabilities. A plugin that didn't declare write:content.page cannot write to pages — not in a sneaky way, not ever. Contrast with WordPress, where any plugin can DROP TABLE users the moment it's activated. Why V8 isolates? They're the same sandbox unit Chrome uses per browser tab. Cheap (microseconds to start), deeply battle-tested, and inherently untrusted ","snippet":"Every plugin runs inside its own V8 isolate (a Dynamic Worker ). A plugin declares a capability manifest up front: { \"name\": \"my-notifier\", \"capabilities\": [ \"read:content.post\", \"network:send\", \"email:send\" ] } The runtime enforces those capabilities. A plugin that didn't declare write:content.page cannot write to pages — not in a sneaky way, not ever. Contrast with WordPress, where any plugin can DROP TABLE users the moment it's activated. Why V8 isolates? They're the same sandbox unit Chrome uses per browser tab. Cheap (microseconds to start), deeply battle-tested, and inherently untrusted "},{"kind":"section","href":"12-plugins.html#first-party-plugins","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","heading":"First-party plugins","text":"First-party plugins A few ship as official packages: Plugin What it does @emdash-cms/plugin-forms Form submissions (included with the blog-cloudflare template). @emdash-cms/plugin-webhook-notifier Fire webhooks on content events. @emdash-cms/plugin-audit-log Track admin actions for compliance.","snippet":"A few ship as official packages: Plugin What it does @emdash-cms/plugin-forms Form submissions (included with the blog-cloudflare template). @emdash-cms/plugin-webhook-notifier Fire webhooks on content events. @emdash-cms/plugin-audit-log Track admin actions for compliance."},{"kind":"section","href":"12-plugins.html#registering-a-plugin","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","heading":"Registering a plugin","text":"Registering a plugin Plugins are registered in astro.config.mjs , in the plugins array passed to the emdash integration: import emdash from 'emdash/astro'; import forms from '@emdash-cms/plugin-forms'; export default defineConfig({ integrations: [ emdash({ adapter: cloudflareAdapter({ /* ... */ }), plugins: [ forms({ submissionsPerMinute: 5, recipients: ['hello@example.com'], }), ], }), ], });","snippet":"Plugins are registered in astro.config.mjs , in the plugins array passed to the emdash integration: import emdash from 'emdash/astro'; import forms from '@emdash-cms/plugin-forms'; export default defineConfig({ integrations: [ emdash({ adapter: cloudflareAdapter({ /* ... */ }), plugins: [ forms({ submissionsPerMinute: 5, recipients: ['hello@example.com'], }), ], }), ], });"},{"kind":"section","href":"12-plugins.html#free-tier-caveat","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","heading":"Free-tier caveat","text":"Free-tier caveat Plugins require the Workers Paid plan. Cloudflare's Dynamic Workers / Worker Loader (the sandbox primitive) is only available on paid accounts ($5/month minimum). On the free plan, comment out the worker_loaders block in wrangler.jsonc and skip plugins. Everything else — admin, content, media, auth — still works.","snippet":"Plugins require the Workers Paid plan. Cloudflare's Dynamic Workers / Worker Loader (the sandbox primitive) is only available on paid accounts ($5/month minimum). On the free plan, comment out the worker_loaders block in wrangler.jsonc and skip plugins. Everything else — admin, content, media, auth — still works."},{"kind":"section","href":"12-plugins.html#the-mcp-server-emdash-s-ai-story","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","heading":"The MCP server — emdash's AI story","text":"The MCP server — emdash's AI story emdash exposes an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server , which means Claude Code, Cursor, and any MCP-compatible agent can read and write content directly — create posts, update schemas, upload media — through authenticated tool calls. This is the \"AI-native\" angle the Cloudflare team emphasized at launch: your CMS talks the same protocol your coding agents do. An agent can: Scaffold new content types based on a natural-language spec. Draft and publish posts with the same permission boundaries as a human editor. Bulk-edit content safely, scoped by role.","snippet":"emdash exposes an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server , which means Claude Code, Cursor, and any MCP-compatible agent can read and write content directly — create posts, update schemas, upload media — through authenticated tool calls. This is the \"AI-native\" angle the Cloudflare team emphasized at launch: your CMS talks the same protocol your coding agents do. An agent can: Scaffold new content types based on a natural-language spec. Draft and publish posts with the same permission boundaries as a human editor. Bulk-edit content safely, scoped by role."},{"kind":"section","href":"12-plugins.html#writing-your-own-plugin","num":"12","sectionName":"Ship","title":"Plugins","heading":"Writing your own plugin","text":"Writing your own plugin A plugin is an npm package that exports a default function. The function receives a capability-scoped API and returns hook handlers: // hello-plugin/src/index.ts import { definePlugin } from '@emdash-cms/plugin-sdk'; export default definePlugin({ name: 'hello', capabilities: ['read:content.post', 'log:write'], hooks: { 'content.published': async (evt, api) => { api.log.info(`Published: ${evt.entry.title}`); }, }, }); Because the plugin runs in an isolate, api is the only way to touch the outside world. There is no fs , no arbitrary fetch , no DB client — just what the host chose to grant.","snippet":"A plugin is an npm package that exports a default function. The function receives a capability-scoped API and returns hook handlers: // hello-plugin/src/index.ts import { definePlugin } from '@emdash-cms/plugin-sdk'; export default definePlugin({ name: 'hello', capabilities: ['read:content.post', 'log:write'], hooks: { 'content.published': async (evt, api) => { api.log.info(`Published: ${evt.entry.title}`); }, }, }); Because the plugin runs in an isolate, api is the only way to touch the outside world. There is no fs , no arbitrary fetch , no DB client — just what the host chose to grant."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"13-api-reference.html","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","text":"Every public function you can import from emdash , its sibling sub-paths, and @emdash-cms/cloudflare . Use this as a lookup when the tutorials don't cover what you need. All imported from \"emdash\" .","snippet":"Every public function you can import from emdash , its sibling sub-paths, and @emdash-cms/cloudflare . Use this as a lookup when the tutorials don't cover what you need."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#entry-point-map","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Entry-point map","text":"Entry-point map Import path When to use emdash All page-level queries: content, taxonomy, settings, SEO, menus, search emdash/runtime The loader and DB handle — use only in live.config.ts or custom server routes emdash/astro The Astro integration default export + storage factories ( local , s3 ) emdash/ui Astro UI components: <Image /> , <PortableText /> , <Comments /> , <WidgetArea /> , etc. emdash/page Page metadata, JSON-LD helpers, plugin <head> hooks emdash/client Typed browser-side REST client ( EmDashClient ) emdash/middleware Request-pipeline helpers for custom routes @emdash-cms/cloudflare Cloudflare","snippet":"Import path When to use emdash All page-level queries: content, taxonomy, settings, SEO, menus, search emdash/runtime The loader and DB handle — use only in live.config.ts or custom server routes emdash/astro The Astro integration default export + storage factories ( local , s3 ) emdash/ui Astro UI components: <Image /> , <PortableText /> , <Comments /> , <WidgetArea /> , etc. emdash/page Page metadata, JSON-LD helpers, plugin <head> hooks emdash/client Typed browser-side REST client ( EmDashClient ) emdash/middleware Request-pipeline helpers for custom routes @emdash-cms/cloudflare Cloudflare"},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#content-queries","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Content queries","text":"Content queries All imported from \"emdash\" . getEmDashCollection(type, filter?) Fetches all entries of a collection type with optional filter, sort, and pagination. Auto-hydrates bylines and taxonomy terms; caches per (type, filter) within a request. import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; const { entries, error, cacheHint, nextCursor } = await getEmDashCollection('posts', { status: 'published', orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, limit: 10, }); Signature: <T, D>(type: T, filter?: CollectionFilter) => Promise<CollectionResult<D>> CollectionFilter: { status?, limit?, cursor?, where?, orderBy?, locale? } Co","snippet":"All imported from \"emdash\" . getEmDashCollection(type, filter?) Fetches all entries of a collection type with optional filter, sort, and pagination. Auto-hydrates bylines and taxonomy terms; caches per (type, filter) within a request. import { getEmDashCollection } from 'emdash'; const { entries, error, cacheHint, nextCursor } = await getEmDashCollection('posts', { status: 'published', orderBy: { publishedAt: 'desc' }, limit: 10, }); Signature: <T, D>(type: T, filter?: CollectionFilter) => Promise<CollectionResult<D>> CollectionFilter: { status?, limit?, cursor?, where?, orderBy?, locale? } Co"},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#taxonomy-terms","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Taxonomy / terms","text":"Taxonomy / terms All imported from \"emdash\" . getTaxonomyTerms(taxonomyName) All terms for a taxonomy, hierarchical tree or flat list depending on its config. getTerm(taxonomyName, slug) One term with its entry count and child terms. getEntryTerms(collection, entryId, taxonomyName?) Terms assigned to a single entry. Pass taxonomyName to restrict to one taxonomy. import { getEntryTerms } from 'emdash'; const tags = await getEntryTerms('posts', post.id, 'tags'); getTermsForEntries(collection, entryIds, taxonomyName) Batch variant — eliminates N+1 queries on list pages. Returns a Map<entryId, TaxonomyTerm[]> . ge","snippet":"All imported from \"emdash\" . getTaxonomyTerms(taxonomyName) All terms for a taxonomy, hierarchical tree or flat list depending on its config. getTerm(taxonomyName, slug) One term with its entry count and child terms. getEntryTerms(collection, entryId, taxonomyName?) Terms assigned to a single entry. Pass taxonomyName to restrict to one taxonomy. import { getEntryTerms } from 'emdash'; const tags = await getEntryTerms('posts', post.id, 'tags'); getTermsForEntries(collection, entryIds, taxonomyName) Batch variant — eliminates N+1 queries on list pages. Returns a Map<entryId, TaxonomyTerm[]> . ge"},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#site-settings","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Site settings","text":"Site settings All imported from \"emdash\" . getSiteSettings() All configured site settings, with media references resolved to full URLs. Includes site title, description, logo, favicon, and any plugin-registered keys. import { getSiteSettings } from 'emdash'; const settings = await getSiteSettings(); // settings.title, settings.description, settings.logo, … getSiteSetting(key) One setting value, with request-scoped caching. getPluginSettings(pluginId) All persisted settings for a registered plugin. getPluginSetting(pluginId, key) One plugin-specific setting value.","snippet":"All imported from \"emdash\" . getSiteSettings() All configured site settings, with media references resolved to full URLs. Includes site title, description, logo, favicon, and any plugin-registered keys. import { getSiteSettings } from 'emdash'; const settings = await getSiteSettings(); // settings.title, settings.description, settings.logo, … getSiteSetting(key) One setting value, with request-scoped caching. getPluginSettings(pluginId) All persisted settings for a registered plugin. getPluginSetting(pluginId, key) One plugin-specific setting value."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#seo","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"SEO","text":"SEO From \"emdash\" . getSeoMeta(content, options?) Resolves a complete SEO metadata object for a content entry. Falls back gracefully: explicit SEO fields → content title/excerpt → site defaults. Builds absolute canonical and OG image URLs. import { getSeoMeta } from 'emdash'; const seo = getSeoMeta(entry, { siteTitle: 'My Blog', siteUrl: 'https://example.com', path: Astro.url.pathname, }); // seo.title, seo.canonical, seo.ogImage, seo.robots … getContentSeo(content) Raw SEO fields from the entry without the template-fallback processing.","snippet":"From \"emdash\" . getSeoMeta(content, options?) Resolves a complete SEO metadata object for a content entry. Falls back gracefully: explicit SEO fields → content title/excerpt → site defaults. Builds absolute canonical and OG image URLs. import { getSeoMeta } from 'emdash'; const seo = getSeoMeta(entry, { siteTitle: 'My Blog', siteUrl: 'https://example.com', path: Astro.url.pathname, }); // seo.title, seo.canonical, seo.ogImage, seo.robots … getContentSeo(content) Raw SEO fields from the entry without the template-fallback processing."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#bylines-authors","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Bylines / authors","text":"Bylines / authors From \"emdash\" . getByline(id) — one byline profile. getBylineBySlug(slug) — by slug. getEntryBylines(collection, entryId) — credits for one entry (falls back to user-linked bylines). getBylinesForEntries(collection, entryIds) — batch variant for list pages.","snippet":"From \"emdash\" . getByline(id) — one byline profile. getBylineBySlug(slug) — by slug. getEntryBylines(collection, entryId) — credits for one entry (falls back to user-linked bylines). getBylinesForEntries(collection, entryIds) — batch variant for list pages."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#navigation-menus","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Navigation menus","text":"Navigation menus getMenu(name) — fetches a nav menu by registered name; returns a resolved tree with URLs interpolated for content and taxonomy items. getMenus() — lists all registered menu definitions (id, name, label).","snippet":"getMenu(name) — fetches a nav menu by registered name; returns a resolved tree with URLs interpolated for content and taxonomy items. getMenus() — lists all registered menu definitions (id, name, label)."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#full-text-search","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Full-text search","text":"Full-text search search(query, options?) — cross-collection FTS5 search. searchCollection(db, collection, query, options?) — scoped to one collection. getSuggestions(db, query, options?) — autocomplete for a partial query. getSearchStats(db) — indexed document counts + FTS5 health. extractPlainText(portableTextBlocks) — utility for building custom indexing pipelines.","snippet":"search(query, options?) — cross-collection FTS5 search. searchCollection(db, collection, query, options?) — scoped to one collection. getSuggestions(db, query, options?) — autocomplete for a partial query. getSearchStats(db) — indexed document counts + FTS5 health. extractPlainText(portableTextBlocks) — utility for building custom indexing pipelines."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#slug-url-utils","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Slug / URL utils","text":"Slug / URL utils decodeSlug(raw) Decodes URI-encoded slug params. Use in [slug].astro before passing to getEmDashEntry . import { decodeSlug, getEmDashEntry } from 'emdash'; const { entry } = await getEmDashEntry('posts', decodeSlug(Astro.params.slug)); slugify(text, maxLength?) Text → URL-safe slug (lowercase, diacritics stripped, hyphens normalized). Default 80-char limit.","snippet":"decodeSlug(raw) Decodes URI-encoded slug params. Use in [slug].astro before passing to getEmDashEntry . import { decodeSlug, getEmDashEntry } from 'emdash'; const { entry } = await getEmDashEntry('posts', decodeSlug(Astro.params.slug)); slugify(text, maxLength?) Text → URL-safe slug (lowercase, diacritics stripped, hyphens normalized). Default 80-char limit."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#i18n","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"i18n","text":"i18n getI18nConfig() — the runtime i18n config, or null . isI18nEnabled() — boolean shortcut. getFallbackChain(locale) — ordered list of locales to try when content in the requested locale is absent. I18nConfig: { defaultLocale, locales, fallback?, prefixDefaultLocale? }","snippet":"getI18nConfig() — the runtime i18n config, or null . isI18nEnabled() — boolean shortcut. getFallbackChain(locale) — ordered list of locales to try when content in the requested locale is absent. I18nConfig: { defaultLocale, locales, fallback?, prefixDefaultLocale? }"},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#page-metadata-json-ld","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Page metadata / JSON-LD","text":"Page metadata / JSON-LD From \"emdash/page\" . getPageRuntime(locals) — retrieves the page runtime from Astro locals ; undefined when emdash isn't initialized. buildBlogPostingJsonLd(...) / buildWebSiteJsonLd(...) — structured-data builders. safeJsonLdSerialize(data) — escaping helper for inline <script type=\"application/ld+json\"> . resolvePageMetadata(...) / renderPageMetadata(...) — plugin-contributed <head> metadata pipeline.","snippet":"From \"emdash/page\" . getPageRuntime(locals) — retrieves the page runtime from Astro locals ; undefined when emdash isn't initialized. buildBlogPostingJsonLd(...) / buildWebSiteJsonLd(...) — structured-data builders. safeJsonLdSerialize(data) — escaping helper for inline <script type=\"application/ld+json\"> . resolvePageMetadata(...) / renderPageMetadata(...) — plugin-contributed <head> metadata pipeline."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#ui-components","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"UI components","text":"UI components Imported from \"emdash/ui\" . All are Astro components. Component Purpose <Image /> (aka <EmDashImage /> ) Optimized media with aspect ratio, srcset, placeholder blur. <PortableText /> Renders Portable Text blocks. Accepts a components override map. <Comments /> Full threaded comment list. <CommentForm /> New-comment submission form. <WidgetArea /> Plugin-registered widget slots. <EmDashHead /> Injects plugin-contributed <head> tags. <EmDashBodyStart /> / <EmDashBodyEnd /> Plugin-contributed body fragments. <PTImage /> , <Code /> , <Embed /> , <Gallery /> , <Columns /> , <Break /> , <HtmlBlock /","snippet":"Imported from \"emdash/ui\" . All are Astro components. Component Purpose <Image /> (aka <EmDashImage /> ) Optimized media with aspect ratio, srcset, placeholder blur. <PortableText /> Renders Portable Text blocks. Accepts a components override map. <Comments /> Full threaded comment list. <CommentForm /> New-comment submission form. <WidgetArea /> Plugin-registered widget slots. <EmDashHead /> Injects plugin-contributed <head> tags. <EmDashBodyStart /> / <EmDashBodyEnd /> Plugin-contributed body fragments. <PTImage /> , <Code /> , <Embed /> , <Gallery /> , <Columns /> , <Break /> , <HtmlBlock /"},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#loader-runtime","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Loader / runtime","text":"Loader / runtime From \"emdash/runtime\" . emdashLoader() — use inside live.config.ts with Astro's defineLiveCollection . Not for page code. getDb() — the ambient Kysely DB handle; for custom server routes and plugins.","snippet":"From \"emdash/runtime\" . emdashLoader() — use inside live.config.ts with Astro's defineLiveCollection . Not for page code. getDb() — the ambient Kysely DB handle; for custom server routes and plugins."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#astro-integration","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Astro integration","text":"Astro integration From \"emdash/astro\" . Default export: emdash(config: EmDashConfig) — register in astro.config.ts . local(config?) — local-filesystem storage factory for EmDashConfig.storage . s3(config) — S3-compatible storage factory.","snippet":"From \"emdash/astro\" . Default export: emdash(config: EmDashConfig) — register in astro.config.ts . local(config?) — local-filesystem storage factory for EmDashConfig.storage . s3(config) — S3-compatible storage factory."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#cloudflare-adapters","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Cloudflare adapters","text":"Cloudflare adapters From \"@emdash-cms/cloudflare\" . Export Purpose cloudflareAdapter (default) Bundles all CF adapters as a preset. d1(config?) D1 database adapter. previewDatabase(config) Durable Object DB for preview/draft serving. playgroundDatabase(config) Durable Object DB for the sandbox. r2(config) R2 media storage adapter. access(config) Cloudflare Access JWT auth adapter. sandbox() Worker Loader plugin sandbox. cloudflareImages(config) Cloudflare Images media provider. cloudflareStream(config) Cloudflare Stream video provider. cloudflareCache(config) Cache API provider configuration.","snippet":"From \"@emdash-cms/cloudflare\" . Export Purpose cloudflareAdapter (default) Bundles all CF adapters as a preset. d1(config?) D1 database adapter. previewDatabase(config) Durable Object DB for preview/draft serving. playgroundDatabase(config) Durable Object DB for the sandbox. r2(config) R2 media storage adapter. access(config) Cloudflare Access JWT auth adapter. sandbox() Worker Loader plugin sandbox. cloudflareImages(config) Cloudflare Images media provider. cloudflareStream(config) Cloudflare Stream video provider. cloudflareCache(config) Cache API provider configuration."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#auth","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Auth","text":"Auth From \"@emdash-cms/auth\" and its sub-paths. Path Export Purpose @emdash-cms/auth createAuth(options) Core auth initializer. @emdash-cms/auth/passkey passkeyProvider() WebAuthn passkey auth. @emdash-cms/auth/oauth/github githubProvider(config) GitHub OAuth. @emdash-cms/auth/oauth/google googleProvider(config) Google OAuth. @emdash-cms/auth/adapters/kysely kyselyAdapter(db) Kysely DB adapter for auth sessions.","snippet":"From \"@emdash-cms/auth\" and its sub-paths. Path Export Purpose @emdash-cms/auth createAuth(options) Core auth initializer. @emdash-cms/auth/passkey passkeyProvider() WebAuthn passkey auth. @emdash-cms/auth/oauth/github githubProvider(config) GitHub OAuth. @emdash-cms/auth/oauth/google googleProvider(config) Google OAuth. @emdash-cms/auth/adapters/kysely kyselyAdapter(db) Kysely DB adapter for auth sessions."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#browser-client","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Browser client","text":"Browser client From \"emdash/client\" — for client-side interactive features. EmDashClient — typed HTTP client for all REST ops (CRUD on content, media, taxonomies, menus, schema). Handles CSRF, auth tokens, optimistic concurrency via _rev . createTransport , csrfInterceptor , tokenInterceptor , devBypassInterceptor — transport factory and interceptor helpers. portableTextToMarkdown / markdownToPortableText — Portable Text ↔ Markdown converters.","snippet":"From \"emdash/client\" — for client-side interactive features. EmDashClient — typed HTTP client for all REST ops (CRUD on content, media, taxonomies, menus, schema). Handles CSRF, auth tokens, optimistic concurrency via _rev . createTransport , csrfInterceptor , tokenInterceptor , devBypassInterceptor — transport factory and interceptor helpers. portableTextToMarkdown / markdownToPortableText — Portable Text ↔ Markdown converters."},{"kind":"section","href":"13-api-reference.html#notable-gaps","num":"13","sectionName":"Reference","title":"API reference","heading":"Notable gaps","text":"Notable gaps No built-in pagination component. Pagination is driven by consuming nextCursor from CollectionResult and passing it back as cursor in the next call. Portable Text rendering is via the UI component only. There's no server-side \"render to HTML string\" utility in the public API — use <PortableText /> . Import from the root, not sub-paths, for queries. getEmDashCollection , getEmDashEntry , getEntryTerms , getSiteSettings are all from \"emdash\" — not \"emdash/content\" . The \"emdash/content\" sub-path re-exports only the Portable Text / Prosemirror converters.","snippet":"No built-in pagination component. Pagination is driven by consuming nextCursor from CollectionResult and passing it back as cursor in the next call. Portable Text rendering is via the UI component only. There's no server-side \"render to HTML string\" utility in the public API — use <PortableText /> . Import from the root, not sub-paths, for queries. getEmDashCollection , getEmDashEntry , getEntryTerms , getSiteSettings are all from \"emdash\" — not \"emdash/content\" . The \"emdash/content\" sub-path re-exports only the Portable Text / Prosemirror converters."},{"kind":"chapter","href":"14-troubleshooting.html","num":"14","sectionName":"Reference","title":"Troubleshooting","text":"The common gotchas, where to go for more, and a suggested week-one learning path. ","snippet":"The common gotchas, where to go for more, and a suggested week-one learning path."},{"kind":"section","href":"14-troubleshooting.html#common-gotchas","num":"14","sectionName":"Reference","title":"Troubleshooting","heading":"Common gotchas","text":"Common gotchas Symptom Likely fix emdash init fails locally Confirm Node 22+ and pnpm 10+. Run corepack enable to activate pnpm. Admin page is blank on Cloudflare Check wrangler.jsonc includes \"nodejs_compat\" in compatibility_flags . D1 migrations don't apply in production You need --remote on any migration command, or it runs against local SQLite. Plugins won't load You're probably on the free plan. Remove the worker_loaders block. Types are stale after schema changes Run npx emdash types . Media uploads fail in dev For Node variant, ensure ./uploads/ is writable. For Cloudflare variant, confirm MEDIA bindi","snippet":"Symptom Likely fix emdash init fails locally Confirm Node 22+ and pnpm 10+. Run corepack enable to activate pnpm. Admin page is blank on Cloudflare Check wrangler.jsonc includes \"nodejs_compat\" in compatibility_flags . D1 migrations don't apply in production You need --remote on any migration command, or it runs against local SQLite. Plugins won't load You're probably on the free plan. Remove the worker_loaders block. Types are stale after schema changes Run npx emdash types . Media uploads fail in dev For Node variant, ensure ./uploads/ is writable. For Cloudflare variant, confirm MEDIA bindi"},{"kind":"section","href":"14-troubleshooting.html#further-reading","num":"14","sectionName":"Reference","title":"Troubleshooting","heading":"Further reading","text":"Further reading Cloudflare blog announcement : blog.cloudflare.com/emdash-wordpress emdash on GitHub : github.com/emdash-cms/emdash Templates repo : github.com/emdash-cms/templates Marketing site & live playground : emdashcms.com Astro docs : docs.astro.build Cloudflare Workers docs : developers.cloudflare.com/workers @astrojs/cloudflare adapter : docs.astro.build/en/guides/integrations-guide/cloudflare","snippet":"Cloudflare blog announcement : blog.cloudflare.com/emdash-wordpress emdash on GitHub : github.com/emdash-cms/emdash Templates repo : github.com/emdash-cms/templates Marketing site & live playground : emdashcms.com Astro docs : docs.astro.build Cloudflare Workers docs : developers.cloudflare.com/workers @astrojs/cloudflare adapter : docs.astro.build/en/guides/integrations-guide/cloudflare"},{"kind":"section","href":"14-troubleshooting.html#a-suggested-5-day-path","num":"14","sectionName":"Reference","title":"Troubleshooting","heading":"A suggested 5-day path","text":"A suggested 5-day path Day 1. Scaffold the blog template with the Cloudflare variant. Run it locally. Create a post in the admin. Change a layout. Day 2. Deploy to Cloudflare. Wire up your own domain. Protect /_emdash/* with Cloudflare Access. Day 3. Define a new content type (e.g. project ) in the admin. Generate types. Build a new page that queries it. Day 4. Pick a first-party plugin (forms or webhooks), enable it on the Paid plan, and wire it into a page. Day 5. Connect the MCP server to Claude Code or Cursor, and author a post entirely through an agent.","snippet":"Day 1. Scaffold the blog template with the Cloudflare variant. Run it locally. Create a post in the admin. Change a layout. Day 2. Deploy to Cloudflare. Wire up your own domain. Protect /_emdash/* with Cloudflare Access. Day 3. Define a new content type (e.g. project ) in the admin. Generate types. Build a new page that queries it. Day 4. Pick a first-party plugin (forms or webhooks), enable it on the Paid plan, and wire it into a page. Day 5. Connect the MCP server to Claude Code or Cursor, and author a post entirely through an agent."},{"kind":"section","href":"14-troubleshooting.html#where-to-get-help","num":"14","sectionName":"Reference","title":"Troubleshooting","heading":"Where to get help","text":"Where to get help GitHub Discussions on the emdash repo — the maintainers require a Discussion before accepting feature PRs, so it's the canonical place for design questions. Issues for reproducible bugs. emdash@cloudflare.com for product feedback. That's the whole surface. emdash is a small idea executed carefully: an Astro integration + a sandbox-first plugin model + the Cloudflare primitives that make scale-to-zero publishing real. Once the five files from chapter 2 live in your head, you can bend it to whatever content shape your project needs.","snippet":"GitHub Discussions on the emdash repo — the maintainers require a Discussion before accepting feature PRs, so it's the canonical place for design questions. Issues for reproducible bugs. emdash@cloudflare.com for product feedback. That's the whole surface. emdash is a small idea executed carefully: an Astro integration + a sandbox-first plugin model + the Cloudflare primitives that make scale-to-zero publishing real. Once the five files from chapter 2 live in your head, you can bend it to whatever content shape your project needs."}];
